System.out.println(formatted); // ËæìÂá∫Ôºö000045 \`\`\` # 3. ‰ΩøÁî®\`DecimalFormat\` \`DecimalFormat\`ÊòØ\`java.text\`ÂåÖ‰∏≠ÁöÑ‰∏Ä‰∏™Á±ªÔºåÂÆÉÂÖÅËÆ∏‰Ω†ÂØπÊï∞Â≠óËøõË°åÊ†ºÂºèÂåñ„ÄÇ \`\`\`java import java.text.DecimalFormat; int number = 7; DecimalFormat format = new DecimalFormat(\\"000000\\"); // Ê†πÊçÆÈúÄË¶ÅË∞ÉÊï¥0ÁöÑÊï∞Èáè String formatted = format.format(number); System.out.println(formatted); // ËæìÂá∫Ôºö000007 \`\`\` # 4. ‰ΩøÁî®\`StringUtils\`ÔºàApache Commons LangÔºâ Â¶ÇÊûú‰Ω†ËÉΩÂú®È°πÁõÆ‰∏≠Ê∑ªÂä†Â§ñÈÉ®Â∫ìÔºå\`StringUtils\` Á±ªÁöÑ \`leftPad\` ÊñπÊ≥ïÊòØ‰∏Ä‰∏™Êñπ‰æøÁöÑËß£ÂÜ≥ÊñπÊ°à„ÄÇÈ¶ñÂÖàÔºåÁ°Æ‰øù‰Ω†ÁöÑÈ°πÁõÆÂåÖÂê´‰∫Ü Apache Commons Lang Â∫ì„ÄÇ \`\`\`java import org.apache.commons.lang3.StringUtils; int number = 123; int length = 6; String numberAsString = Integer.toString(number); String paddedString = StringUtils.leftPad(numberAsString, length, '0'); System.out.println(paddedString); // ËæìÂá∫Ôºö000123 \`\`\` ËøôÁßçÊñπÊ≥ïÁöÑÂ•ΩÂ§ÑÊòØ‰ª£Á†ÅÊõ¥ÁÆÄÊ¥ÅÊòìËØªÔºåÁâπÂà´ÊòØÂú®Â§ÑÁêÜ‰∏ç‰ªÖÈôê‰∫éÊï∞Â≠ó„ÄÅ‰πüÂèØËÉΩÈúÄË¶ÅÂØπÂ≠óÁ¨¶‰∏≤ËøõË°åÊìç‰ΩúÁöÑÊÉÖÂΩ¢‰∏ã„ÄÇ‰∏çËøáÔºåÂÆÉË¶ÅÊ±Ç‰Ω†Ê∑ªÂä†Apache Commons LangÂ∫ì‰Ωú‰∏∫È°πÁõÆ‰æùËµñ„ÄÇ # ÈÄâÊã©ÊúÄ‰Ω≥ÊñπÊ≥ï ÈÄâÊã©Âì™ÁßçÊñπÊ≥ïÂèñÂÜ≥‰∫é‰Ω†ÁöÑÂÖ∑‰ΩìÈúÄÊ±Ç‰∏éÁéØÂ¢ÉÔºö - Â¶ÇÊûú‰∏çÂ∏åÊúõÊ∑ªÂä†È¢ùÂ§ñÁöÑÂ∫ì‰æùËµñÔºå‰ΩøÁî®\`String.format()\`Êàñ\`DecimalFormat\`„ÄÇ - ÂØπ‰∫éÁÆÄÂçïÁöÑÊï∞Â≠óÂ°´ÂÖÖÔºå\`String.format()\`ÊòØÊúÄÁõ¥Êé•ÁöÑÊñπÂºè„ÄÇ - Âá∫‰∫éÊ†ºÂºèÂåñÁöÑÂ§çÊùÇÊÄßÔºåÂèØ‰ª•ÈÄâÊã©\`DecimalFormat\`„ÄÇ - Â¶ÇÊûúÈ°πÁõÆÂ∑≤Áªè‰æùËµñApache Commons LangÊàñÂØπÂ≠óÁ¨¶‰∏≤Â§ÑÁêÜÊúâÊõ¥ÂπøÊ≥õÁöÑÈúÄÊ±ÇÔºå\`StringUtils.leftPad()\`‰ºöÊòØ‰∏™‰∏çÈîôÁöÑÈÄâÊã©„ÄÇ"},{"instruction":"pythonÊâìÂºÄÊñá‰ª∂ËßÜÈ¢ëÁöÑÊñπÊ≥ï","output":"Âú®Python‰∏≠ÊâìÂºÄÂíåÊí≠ÊîæËßÜÈ¢ëÊñá‰ª∂ÔºåÈÄöÂ∏∏ÈúÄË¶Å‰ΩøÁî®Á¨¨‰∏âÊñπÂ∫ìÔºåÂõ†‰∏∫PythonÊ†áÂáÜÂ∫ìÊú¨Ë∫´‰∏çÁõ¥Êé•ÊîØÊåÅËßÜÈ¢ëÊñá‰ª∂ÁöÑÊí≠Êîæ„ÄÇ‰∏Ä‰∏™Â∏∏Áî®‰∏îÂº∫Â§ßÁöÑÁ¨¨‰∏âÊñπÂ∫ìÊòØ\`OpenCV\`ÔºàOpen Source Computer Vision LibraryÔºâ„ÄÇ\`OpenCV\`‰∏ªË¶ÅÁî®‰∫éËÆ°ÁÆóÊú∫ËßÜËßâ„ÄÅÂõæÂÉèÂ§ÑÁêÜÂíåÊú∫Âô®Â≠¶‰π†È¢ÜÂüüÔºå‰ΩÜÂÆÉ‰πüËÉΩÂæàÂ•ΩÂú∞Áî®Êù•Êí≠ÊîæËßÜÈ¢ëÊñá‰ª∂„ÄÇ ‰ª•‰∏ãÊòØ‰ΩøÁî®\`OpenCV\`Âú®Python‰∏≠ÊâìÂºÄÂíåÊí≠ÊîæËßÜÈ¢ëÊñá‰ª∂ÁöÑÂü∫Êú¨Ê≠•È™§Ôºö 1. **ÂÆâË£ÖOpenCV**ÔºöÈ¶ñÂÖàÔºå‰Ω†ÈúÄË¶ÅÂÆâË£Ö\`OpenCV\`„ÄÇÂ¶ÇÊûú‰Ω†ËøòÊ≤°ÊúâÂÆâË£ÖÔºåÂèØ‰ª•ÈÄöËøápipÂÆâË£Ö\`opencv-python\`ÂåÖ„ÄÇ \`\`\`bash pip install opencv-python \`\`\` 2. **‰ΩøÁî®OpenCVÊí≠ÊîæËßÜÈ¢ë**ÔºöÊé•‰∏ãÊù•Ôºå‰Ω†ÂèØ‰ª•‰ΩøÁî®\`cv2.VideoCapture\`Êù•ËØªÂèñËßÜÈ¢ëÊñá‰ª∂ÔºåÁÑ∂ÂêéÈÄêÂ∏ßÊòæÁ§∫„ÄÇ Á§∫‰æã‰ª£Á†ÅÂ¶Ç‰∏ãÔºö \`\`\`python import cv2 # ËßÜÈ¢ëÊñá‰ª∂ÁöÑË∑ØÂæÑ video_path = 'your_video_file.mp4' # ‰ΩøÁî®OpenCVÊâìÂºÄËßÜÈ¢ë cap = cv2.VideoCapture(video_path) # Ê£ÄÊü•ÊòØÂê¶ÊàêÂäüÊâìÂºÄ if not cap.isOpened(): print(\\"Error: Could not open video.\\") exit() # ÈÄêÂ∏ßËØªÂèñËßÜÈ¢ë while True: # retÊòØ‰∏Ä‰∏™Â∏ÉÂ∞îÂÄºÔºåË°®Á§∫ÊòØÂê¶ÊàêÂäüËØªÂèñÂ∏ßÔºåframeÊòØÊØè‰∏ÄÂ∏ßÁöÑÂõæÂÉèÔºåÊòØ‰∏Ä‰∏™numpyÊï∞ÁªÑ ret, frame = cap.read() # Â¶ÇÊûúÊ≠£Á°ÆËØªÂèñÂ∏ßÔºåret‰∏∫True if not ret: print(\\"Can't receive frame (stream end?). Exiting ...\\") break # ÊòæÁ§∫Â∏ß cv2.imshow('Frame', frame) # Êåâ'q'ÈÄÄÂá∫ if cv2.waitKey(1) == ord('q'): break # ÂÆåÊàêÂêéÈáäÊîæÊçïËé∑Âô®ÂíåÈîÄÊØÅÊâÄÊúâOpenCVÁ™óÂè£ cap.release() cv2.destroyAllWindows() \`\`\` Ëøô‰∏™‰æãÂ≠êÂ±ïÁ§∫‰∫ÜÂ¶Ç‰ΩïÊâìÂºÄ‰∏Ä‰∏™ËßÜÈ¢ëÊñá‰ª∂ÔºåÈÄêÂ∏ßËØªÂèñÂπ∂ÊòæÁ§∫„ÄÇ\`cv2.waitKey(1)\`ÊòØÁî®‰∫éÊöÇÂÅúÂ∏ßÊòæÁ§∫Êó∂Èó¥Ôºå‰ΩøÂæóËßÜÈ¢ëËÉΩ‰ª•Ê≠£Â∏∏ÈÄüÂ∫¶Êí≠Êîæ„ÄÇÊåâ‰∏ã'q'ÈîÆÂèØ‰ª•ÊèêÂâçÁªàÊ≠¢ËßÜÈ¢ëÁöÑÊí≠Êîæ„ÄÇ Ê≥®ÊÑèÔºöÊ≠§‰ª£Á†Å‰ªÖÈÄÇÁî®‰∫éÂÖ∑ÊúâÂõæÂΩ¢ÁïåÈù¢ÁöÑÁ≥ªÁªüÁéØÂ¢ÉÔºåÂ¶ÇÊûú‰Ω†Âú®Ê≤°ÊúâÂõæÂΩ¢ÁïåÈù¢ÁöÑÊúçÂä°Âô®‰∏äËøêË°åÂÆÉÔºà‰æãÂ¶ÇÈÄöËøáSSHËøûÊé•ÔºâÔºåÂàôÈúÄË¶ÅÂØªÊâæÂÖ∂‰ªñÊñπÊ≥ïÊòæÁ§∫ÊàñÂ§ÑÁêÜËßÜÈ¢ëÂ∏ß„ÄÇ Ê≠§Â§ñÔºå\`OpenCV\`Êõ¥Â§öÁöÑÊòØ‰Ωú‰∏∫Â§ÑÁêÜÂíåÂàÜÊûêËßÜÈ¢ëÁöÑÂ∑•ÂÖ∑ÔºåËÄå‰∏çÊòØ‰∏Ä‰∏™‰∏ìÈó®ÁöÑËßÜÈ¢ëÊí≠ÊîæÂô®„ÄÇÂ¶ÇÊûú‰Ω†ÁöÑÁõÆÁöÑÂè™ÊòØ‰∏∫‰∫ÜÊí≠ÊîæËßÜÈ¢ëÔºåÂèØËÉΩÈúÄË¶ÅËÄÉËôëÂÖ∂‰ªñ‰∏ìÈó®ÁöÑËßÜÈ¢ëÊí≠ÊîæÂ∫ìÊàñËÄÖËΩØ‰ª∂„ÄÇ"},{"instruction":"opencvÂ∫ì‰∏≠ÊúâÊ≤°ÊúâÂÆûÁé∞ÂØπËßÜÈ¢ë‰∏≠Âá∫Áé∞ÁöÑÂèØÁßªÂä®Áâ©‰ΩìÊäìÊãçÁöÑÂáΩÊï∞","output":"OpenCVÊèê‰æõ‰∫ÜÂ§öÁßçÊñπÊ≥ïÊù•Ê£ÄÊµãËßÜÈ¢ë‰∏≠ÁöÑÁßªÂä®Áâ©‰ΩìÔºåÂπ∂‰∏îÂèØ‰ª•Ê†πÊçÆËøô‰∫õÊñπÊ≥ïÊù•ÂÆûÁé∞ÂØπÁßªÂä®Áâ©‰ΩìÁöÑÊäìÊãç„ÄÇËôΩÁÑ∂Ê≤°Êúâ‰∏Ä‰∏™Áõ¥Êé•ÁöÑÂáΩÊï∞ÂèØ‰ª•‰∏ÄÊ≠•Âà∞‰ΩçÂÆåÊàêËøô‰∏™‰ªªÂä°Ôºå‰ΩÜÈÄöËøáÁªìÂêà‰ΩøÁî®ËÉåÊôØÂáèÈô§ÔºàBackground SubtractionÔºâÊñπÊ≥ï„ÄÅËΩÆÂªìÊ£ÄÊµãÔºàContour DetectionÔºâ‰ª•Âèä‰∏Ä‰∫õÂõæÂÉèÂ§ÑÁêÜÊäÄÊúØÔºåÊàë‰ª¨ÂèØ‰ª•ÊûÑÂª∫‰∏Ä‰∏™ÊäìÊãçÁßªÂä®Áâ©‰ΩìÁöÑËß£ÂÜ≥ÊñπÊ°à„ÄÇ # Âü∫Êú¨Ê≠•È™§ 1. **ËÉåÊôØÂáèÈô§** OpenCVÊèê‰æõ‰∫ÜÂá†ÁßçËÉåÊôØÂáèÈô§ÁÆóÊ≥ïÔºå‰æãÂ¶Ç\`cv2.createBackgroundSubtractorMOG2()\`Âíå\`cv2.createBackgroundSubtractorKNN()\`ÔºåÁî®‰∫éÂàÜÁ¶ªËßÜÈ¢ë‰∏≠ÁöÑÂâçÊôØÁâ©‰ΩìÔºàÂç≥ÁßªÂä®Áâ©‰ΩìÔºâÂíåËÉåÊôØ„ÄÇËøô‰∫õÊñπÊ≥ïÂèØ‰ª•Â∏ÆÂä©Êàë‰ª¨ËØÜÂà´Âá∫ËßÜÈ¢ëÂ∏ß‰∏≠ÁöÑÁßªÂä®ÈÉ®ÂàÜ„ÄÇ 2. **ÂØªÊâæËΩÆÂªì** ‰ΩøÁî®\`cv2.findContours()\`ÂáΩÊï∞ÔºåÂèØ‰ª•Âü∫‰∫éÁªèËøáËÉåÊôØÂáèÈô§Â§ÑÁêÜÂêéÁöÑ‰∫åÂÄºÂõæÂÉèÊù•ÂØªÊâæÁßªÂä®Áâ©‰ΩìÁöÑËΩÆÂªì„ÄÇÈÄöËøáÁ≠õÈÄâ‰∏ÄÂÆöÂ§ßÂ∞èÁöÑËΩÆÂªìÔºåÂèØ‰ª•Ëøõ‰∏ÄÊ≠•Á°ÆÂÆöÊÑüÂÖ¥Ë∂£ÁöÑÁßªÂä®Áâ©‰Ωì„ÄÇ 3. **ÊäìÊãçÁßªÂä®Áâ©‰Ωì** ÂΩìÊàë‰ª¨Á°ÆÂÆö‰∫ÜÁßªÂä®Áâ©‰ΩìÁöÑ‰ΩçÁΩÆÂêéÔºåÂèØ‰ª•Ê†πÊçÆÁâ©‰ΩìÁöÑËΩÆÂªìÊàñËæπÁïåÊ°ÜÊäìÊãçÔºàÂç≥Êà™ÂèñÔºâËØ•ÁßªÂä®Áâ©‰ΩìÁöÑÂõæÂÉè„ÄÇ # ÂÆûÁé∞Á§∫‰æã ‰ª•‰∏ãÊòØ‰∏Ä‰∏™ÁÆÄÂåñÁöÑÂÆûÁé∞Á§∫‰æãÔºåÂ±ïÁ§∫‰∫ÜÂ¶Ç‰Ωï‰ΩøÁî®ËÉåÊôØÂáèÈô§ÂíåËΩÆÂªìÊ£ÄÊµãÊù•ËØÜÂà´Âπ∂ÊäìÊãçÁßªÂä®Áâ©‰Ωì„ÄÇ \`\`\`python import cv2 # ÂàùÂßãÂåñËÉåÊôØÂáèÈô§Âô® backSub = cv2.createBackgroundSubtractorMOG2() # ÊâìÂºÄËßÜÈ¢ë cap = cv2.VideoCapture('your_video_file.mp4') if not cap.isOpened(): print(\\"Error: Could not open video.\\") exit() while True: ret, frame = cap.read() if not ret: break # Â∫îÁî®ËÉåÊôØÂáèÈô§ fgMask = backSub.apply(frame) # ÂØªÊâæËΩÆÂªì contours, _ = cv2.findContours(fgMask, cv2.RETR_EXTERNAL, cv2.CHAIN_APPROX_SIMPLE) for cnt in contours: # ËøáÊª§Â∞èËΩÆÂªì if cv2.contourArea(cnt) > 500: # ÁªòÂà∂ËæπÁïåÊ°Ü x, y, w, h = cv2.boundingRect(cnt) cv2.rectangle(frame, (x, y), (x+w, y+h), (0, 255, 0), 2) # ÊäìÊãçÁßªÂä®Áâ©‰Ωì moving_object_img = frame[y:y+h, x:x+w] # ÊòæÁ§∫Â∏¶ÊúâËæπÁïåÊ°ÜÁöÑÂ∏ß cv2.imshow('Frame', frame) # Êåâ'q'ÈÄÄÂá∫ if cv2.waitKey(30) & 0xFF == ord('q'): break cap.release() cv2.destroyAllWindows() \`\`\` Ëøô‰∏™ËÑöÊú¨ËØªÂèñ‰∏Ä‰∏™ËßÜÈ¢ëÊñá‰ª∂Ôºå‰ΩøÁî®MOG2ËÉåÊôØÂáèÈô§ÁÆóÊ≥ïÊù•ÂàÜÁ¶ªÁßªÂä®Áâ©‰ΩìÂπ∂ÈÄöËøáËΩÆÂªìÊ£ÄÊµãÊ†áËØÜÂá∫ÁßªÂä®Áâ©‰Ωì„ÄÇÂØπ‰∫éÊØè‰∏™ËæÉÂ§ßÁöÑÁßªÂä®Áâ©‰ΩìÔºåÂÆÉÁªòÂà∂‰∏Ä‰∏™ÁªøËâ≤ÁöÑËæπÁïåÊ°ÜÂπ∂ÊäìÊãçËØ•Áâ©‰ΩìÁöÑÂõæÂÉèÔºàÂ∞ΩÁÆ°Âú®Ëøô‰∏™Âü∫Êú¨Á§∫‰æã‰∏≠ÔºåÊäìÊãçÁöÑÂõæÂÉèÊ≤°ÊúâË¢´‰øùÂ≠òÊàñÊòæÁ§∫Ôºå‰Ω†ÂèØ‰ª•Ê†πÊçÆÈúÄË¶ÅÊ∑ªÂä†‰ª£Á†ÅÊù•‰øùÂ≠òÊàñËøõ‰∏ÄÊ≠•Â§ÑÁêÜËøô‰∫õÂõæÂÉèÔºâ„ÄÇ ËØ∑Ê≥®ÊÑèÔºåÂÆûÈôÖÂ∫îÁî®‰∏≠ÂèØËÉΩÈúÄË¶ÅË∞ÉÊï¥ËÉåÊôØÂáèÈô§ÊñπÊ≥ïÁöÑÂèÇÊï∞„ÄÅËΩÆÂªìËøáÊª§ÁöÑÈòàÂÄºÁ≠âÔºå‰ª•ÈÄÇÂ∫î‰∏çÂêåÁöÑËßÜÈ¢ëÂÜÖÂÆπÂíåÂú∫ÊôØ„ÄÇ"},{"instruction":"Êó†Ê≥ïËøêË°å","output":"Â¶ÇÊûú‰Ω†ÈÅáÂà∞Êó†Ê≥ïËøêË°å‰∏äËø∞‰ª£Á†ÅÁöÑÈóÆÈ¢òÔºåËøôÂèØËÉΩÁî±Âá†‰∏™‰∏çÂêåÁöÑÂõ†Á¥†ÂºïËµ∑„ÄÇËÆ©Êàë‰ª¨‰∏ÄÊ≠•‰∏ÄÊ≠•Âú∞ÊéíÊü•ÂíåËß£ÂÜ≥Ëøô‰∫õÂèØËÉΩÁöÑÈóÆÈ¢òÔºö # 1. OpenCVÊú™Ê≠£Á°ÆÂÆâË£Ö È¶ñÂÖàÔºåËØ∑Á°Æ‰øù‰Ω†Â∑≤ÁªèÊ≠£Á°ÆÂÆâË£Ö‰∫Ü\`opencv-python\`Â∫ì„ÄÇÂèØ‰ª•ÈÄöËøáÂú®ÁªàÁ´ØÊàñÂëΩ‰ª§ÊèêÁ§∫Á¨¶‰∏≠ËøêË°å‰ª•‰∏ãÂëΩ‰ª§Êù•Ê£ÄÊü•Ôºö \`\`\`bash pip show opencv-python \`\`\` Â¶ÇÊûúËøô‰∏™ÂëΩ‰ª§Ê≤°ÊúâËøîÂõû‰ªª‰ΩïÂÜÖÂÆπÔºåË°®Á§∫‰Ω†ËøòÊ≤°ÊúâÂÆâË£Ö\`opencv-python\`„ÄÇËØ∑ÈÄöËøá‰ª•‰∏ãÂëΩ‰ª§ÂÆâË£ÖÔºö \`\`\`bash pip install opencv-python \`\`\` # 2. ËßÜÈ¢ëÊñá‰ª∂Ë∑ØÂæÑÈîôËØØ Á°Æ‰øù‰Ω†Âú®‰ª£Á†Å‰∏≠ËÆæÁΩÆÁöÑËßÜÈ¢ëÊñá‰ª∂Ë∑ØÂæÑÊòØÊ≠£Á°ÆÁöÑ„ÄÇÂ¶ÇÊûúÊñá‰ª∂Ë∑ØÂæÑÈîôËØØÊàñÊñá‰ª∂‰∏çÂ≠òÂú®ÔºåOpenCVÂ∞ÜÊó†Ê≥ïÊâìÂºÄËßÜÈ¢ëÊñá‰ª∂„ÄÇ‰Ω†ÂèØ‰ª•Â∞ùËØïÂ∞ÜËßÜÈ¢ëÊñá‰ª∂Ë∑ØÂæÑ‰øÆÊîπ‰∏∫ÁªùÂØπË∑ØÂæÑÔºåÊàñÂ∞ÜËßÜÈ¢ëÊñá‰ª∂ÊîæÂú®‰∏éPythonËÑöÊú¨Áõ∏ÂêåÁöÑÁõÆÂΩï‰∏ãÔºåÂπ∂‰ΩøÁî®Áõ∏ÂØπË∑ØÂæÑ„ÄÇ # 3. Êñá‰ª∂ÁºñÁ†ÅÊàñÊ†ºÂºèÈóÆÈ¢ò Êúâ‰∫õËßÜÈ¢ëÊñá‰ª∂ÁöÑÁºñÁ†ÅÊàñÊ†ºÂºèÂèØËÉΩ‰∏çË¢´OpenCVÊîØÊåÅÔºåÂ∞ùËØï‰ΩøÁî®‰∏Ä‰∏™Â∏∏ËßÅÊ†ºÂºèÂíåÁºñÁ†ÅÁöÑËßÜÈ¢ëÊñá‰ª∂ÔºåÊØîÂ¶Ç‰∏Ä‰∏™MP4Êñá‰ª∂ÔºåÁî®H.264ÁºñÁ†Å„ÄÇ # 4. ÂÖ∂‰ªñÂèØËÉΩÁöÑÈóÆÈ¢ò - **PythonÁâàÊú¨ÈóÆÈ¢ò**ÔºöÁ°ÆËÆ§‰Ω†‰ΩøÁî®ÁöÑPythonÁâàÊú¨‰∏éÂÆâË£ÖÁöÑOpenCVÁâàÊú¨ÂÖºÂÆπ„ÄÇ - **ÊùÉÈôêÈóÆÈ¢ò**ÔºöÁ°Æ‰øù‰Ω†ÊúâÊùÉÈôêËØªÂèñËßÜÈ¢ëÊñá‰ª∂ÔºåÁâπÂà´ÊòØÂú®LinuxÊàñmacOSÁ≥ªÁªü‰∏ä„ÄÇ - **ÂõæÂΩ¢Áî®Êà∑ÁïåÈù¢(GUI)ÈóÆÈ¢ò**ÔºöÂ¶ÇÊûú‰Ω†Âú®Ê≤°ÊúâGUIÁöÑÊúçÂä°Âô®‰∏äËøêË°åÊ≠§ËÑöÊú¨Ôºà‰æãÂ¶ÇÈÄöËøáSSHËøûÊé•Âà∞‰∏Ä‰∏™Ê≤°ÊúâÊ°åÈù¢ÁéØÂ¢ÉÁöÑLinuxÊúçÂä°Âô®Ôºâ, OpenCVÂèØËÉΩÊó†Ê≥ïÂàõÂª∫Á™óÂè£„ÄÇÂú®ËøôÁßçÊÉÖÂÜµ‰∏ãÔºå‰Ω†ÂèØ‰ª•Â∞ùËØïÂè™‰øùÂ≠òÊ£ÄÊµãÂà∞ÁöÑÂõæÂÉèÔºåËÄå‰∏çÊòØÂ∞ùËØïÊòæÁ§∫ÂÆÉ‰ª¨„ÄÇ # 5. Ê£ÄÊü•ÈîôËØØ‰ø°ÊÅØ ‰ªîÁªÜÈòÖËØªÊä•Èîô‰ø°ÊÅØÔºåÂÆÉÂèØ‰ª•Áªô‰Ω†Êèê‰æõ‰∏∫‰ªÄ‰πàËÑöÊú¨Êó†Ê≥ïËøêË°åÁöÑÁ∫øÁ¥¢„ÄÇÊØîÂ¶ÇÔºåÂ¶ÇÊûúÊä•Èîô‰ø°ÊÅØÊòØÂÖ≥‰∫éÊó†Ê≥ïÂä†ËΩΩÊüê‰∏™Ê®°ÂùóÊàñÂ∫ìÁöÑÔºåÈÇ£ÂèØËÉΩÂ∞±ÊòØÁéØÂ¢ÉÈÖçÁΩÆÈóÆÈ¢òÔºõÂ¶ÇÊûúÈîôËØØÊòØÂÖ≥‰∫éÊñá‰ª∂Êó†Ê≥ïÊâæÂà∞ÁöÑÔºåÈÇ£Â∞±ÊòØË∑ØÂæÑÈóÆÈ¢òÔºõÂ¶ÇÊûúÊ≤°Êúâ‰ªª‰ΩïÈîôËØØ‰ø°ÊÅØÔºå‰ΩÜÊòØËÑöÊú¨Á™ÅÁÑ∂ÁªàÊ≠¢ÔºåÂèØËÉΩÊòØÁî±‰∫éÊñá‰ª∂Ê†ºÂºèÊàñÁºñÁ†ÅÈóÆÈ¢ò„ÄÇ Â¶ÇÊûú‰∏äËø∞Ê≠•È™§‰ªçÁÑ∂Êó†Ê≥ïËß£ÂÜ≥‰Ω†ÁöÑÈóÆÈ¢òÔºåËØ∑ÁªôÂá∫Êõ¥ÂÖ∑‰ΩìÁöÑÈîôËØØÊèèËø∞ÊàñÊä•Èîô‰ø°ÊÅØÔºåËøôÊ†∑Â∞±ËÉΩÊõ¥Á≤æÁ°ÆÂú∞ÂÆö‰ΩçÈóÆÈ¢ò„ÄÇ"},{"instruction":"SyntaxError: EOL while scanning string literal","output":"\`SyntaxError: EOL while scanning string literal\` ÈîôËØØÈÄöÂ∏∏ÂèëÁîüÂú®PythonËß£ÊûêÂô®ÈÅáÂà∞Êú™Ê≠£Á°ÆÁªìÊùüÁöÑÂ≠óÁ¨¶‰∏≤Â≠óÈù¢ÈáèÊó∂„ÄÇËøôÊÑèÂë≥ÁùÄ‰Ω†ÁöÑ‰ª£Á†Å‰∏≠Êúâ‰∏Ä‰∏™ÂºÄÂêØÁöÑÂºïÂè∑ÔºàÂçïÂºïÂè∑\`'\`ÊàñÂèåÂºïÂè∑\`\\"\`ÔºâÔºå‰ΩÜÊòØPythonÂú®Âêå‰∏ÄË°åÁªìÊùü‰πãÂâçÊ≤°ÊúâÊâæÂà∞Áõ∏ÂåπÈÖçÁöÑÈó≠ÂêàÂºïÂè∑„ÄÇËøôÁßçÈîôËØØÂæàÂ∏∏ËßÅÔºåÁâπÂà´ÊòØÂú®Â§ÑÁêÜÂåÖÂê´Ë∑ØÂæÑÊàñÈïøÂ≠óÁ¨¶‰∏≤Êó∂„ÄÇ‰∏ãÈù¢ÊòØÂá†‰∏™Â∏∏ËßÅÁöÑÂéüÂõ†ÂèäÂÖ∂Ëß£ÂÜ≥ÊñπÊ≥ïÔºö # ÂéüÂõ†1ÔºöÂ≠óÁ¨¶‰∏≤Êú™Èó≠Âêà **‰æãÂ≠êÔºö** \`\`\`python print(\\"This is an example \`\`\` **Ëß£ÂÜ≥ÊñπÊ≥ïÔºö** Á°Æ‰øùÂ≠óÁ¨¶‰∏≤Ë¢´Ê≠£Á°ÆÈó≠Âêà„ÄÇ \`\`\`python print(\\"This is an example\\") \`\`\` # ÂéüÂõ†2ÔºöË∑ØÂæÑÂ≠óÁ¨¶‰∏≤‰∏≠ÁöÑÂèçÊñúÊù† Âú®WindowsÁ≥ªÁªü‰∏≠ÔºåË∑ØÂæÑÈÄöÂ∏∏ÂåÖÂê´ÂèçÊñúÊù†\`\`‰Ωú‰∏∫ÁõÆÂΩïÂàÜÈöîÁ¨¶Ôºå‰ΩÜÂú®PythonÂ≠óÁ¨¶‰∏≤‰∏≠ÔºåÂèçÊñúÊù†ÊúâÁâπÊÆäÂê´‰πâÔºåÁî®‰ΩúËΩ¨‰πâÂ≠óÁ¨¶„ÄÇ **‰æãÂ≠êÔºö** \`\`\`python file_path = \\"C:pathtoyourfile.txt\\" \`\`\` **Ëß£ÂÜ≥ÊñπÊ≥ïÔºö** - ‰ΩøÁî®ÂéüÂßãÂ≠óÁ¨¶‰∏≤ÔºåÂú®Â≠óÁ¨¶‰∏≤ÂâçÂä†\`r\`Êù•ÂëäËØâPython‰∏çÂ§ÑÁêÜÂèçÊñúÊù†‰Ωú‰∏∫ËΩ¨‰πâÂ≠óÁ¨¶„ÄÇ \`\`\`python file_path = r\\"C:pathtoyourfile.txt\\" \`\`\` - ÊàñËÄÖ‰ΩøÁî®ÂèåÂèçÊñúÊù†\`\`Êù•ÈÅøÂÖçËΩ¨‰πâ„ÄÇ \`\`\`python file_path = \\"C:pathtoyourfile.txt\\" \`\`\` - Âè¶Â§ñÔºå‰πüÂèØ‰ª•‰ΩøÁî®Ê≠£ÊñúÊù†\`/\`ÔºåPythonÂèØ‰ª•ÂæàÂ•ΩÂú∞Â§ÑÁêÜËøôÁßçÊÉÖÂÜµ„ÄÇ \`\`\`python file_path = \\"C:/path/to/your/file.txt\\" \`\`\` # ÂéüÂõ†3ÔºöÂ≠óÁ¨¶‰∏≤Ë∑®Â§öË°å Â¶ÇÊûú‰Ω†ÊâìÁÆóÂàõÂª∫‰∏Ä‰∏™Ë∑®Â§öË°åÁöÑÂ≠óÁ¨¶‰∏≤Ôºå‰ΩÜÊ≤°Êúâ‰ΩøÁî®‰∏âÂºïÂè∑Ôºà\`'''\`Êàñ\`\\"\\"\\"\`ÔºâÊù•ÂÆö‰πâÂÆÉ„ÄÇ **‰æãÂ≠êÔºö** \`\`\`python long_string = \\"This is a long string that spans multiple lines\\" \`\`\` **Ëß£ÂÜ≥ÊñπÊ≥ïÔºö** ‰ΩøÁî®‰∏âÂºïÂè∑Êù•ÂÆö‰πâË∑®Â§öË°åÁöÑÂ≠óÁ¨¶‰∏≤„ÄÇ \`\`\`python long_string = \\"\\"\\"This is a long string that spans multiple lines\\"\\"\\" \`\`\` ‰øÆÂ§ç‰ª•‰∏äÈóÆÈ¢òÂêéÔºå\`SyntaxError: EOL while scanning string literal\` ÈîôËØØÂ∫îËØ•‰ºöË¢´Ëß£ÂÜ≥„ÄÇÁ°Æ‰øùÊ£ÄÊü•‰Ω†ÁöÑÂ≠óÁ¨¶‰∏≤Â≠óÈù¢ÈáèÔºåÁ°Æ‰øùÂÆÉ‰ª¨Ë¢´Ê≠£Á°ÆÈó≠Âêà‰∏îÊ≠£Á°ÆÂ§ÑÁêÜË∑®Ë°åÂíåË∑ØÂæÑÂ≠óÁ¨¶‰∏≤ÊÉÖÂÜµ„ÄÇ"},{"instruction":"you're my english teacher my level is a1","output":"Welcome! It's great that you're eager to learn English. As your A1 level English teacher, we'll start with the basics and gradually build up your skills. The A1 level is the beginning level where we focus on simple phrases, basic vocabulary, and very simple grammatical structures. Let's get started with some fundamental areas you'll need to know as an A1 learner. # Vocabulary At this level, it's important to concentrate on everyday words that will help you describe your environment, simple actions, and yourself. Here are a few basic categories we will cover: - **Numbers** (one, two, three, ...) - **Colors** (red, blue, yellow, ...) - **Family members** (mother, father, brother, sister) - **Days of the week** - **Simple adjectives** (big, small, happy, sad) # Grammar We will start with the most basic grammatical concepts including: - **Subject pronouns** (I, you, he, she, it, we, they) - **Be verb** in its simple forms (am, is, are). For example, \\"I am a student,\\" \\"You are a teacher.\\" - **Simple present tense** for routines and habits. E.g., \\"I go to school.\\" - **Articles** (a, an, the). Knowing when to use them can be tricky, but we'll practice. - **Prepositions of place** (at, in, on) to describe where things are. E.g., \\"The book is on the table.\\" # Communication Your ability to communicate in real-life situations is the main goal. We will work on: - **Introducing yourself** and others - **Describing your family, home, and daily routines** - **Asking and answering simple questions** about personal details. E.g., \\"What‚Äôs your name?\\" \\"Where do you live?\\" # Skills Development In addition to vocabulary and grammar, we'll focus on the four key language skills: - **Listening**: Understanding basic greetings, introductions, and other simple spoken information. - **Speaking**: Participating in brief conversations using simple sentences. - **Reading**: Identifying familiar words and phrases in simple texts. - **Writing**: Writing simple phrases and sentences about yourself and filling in forms with personal details. # Practice - Practice is key to learning a new language. Try to use English in your daily activities. Even thinking to yourself in English can help! - Listening to English songs, watching children's shows in English, or using educational apps designed for ESL learners can be very beneficial. Remember, learning a new language is a journey. It takes time, patience, and practice. Don't be afraid to make mistakes; they're a natural part of the learning process. I'm here to guide, support, and help you through your English learning adventure. Let's embark on this exciting journey together!"},{"instruction":"role play with me, talk and you break down my sentence","output":"Of course! Let's do a simple role-play exercise. I'll start by giving you a scenario, and you respond as if you're in that scenario. Then, I'll provide feedback on your sentence, breaking it down to help you understand and improve. # Scenario: Imagine you're at a coffee shop in an English-speaking country, and you want to order a cup of coffee and a piece of cake. The barista greets you and asks what you would like to order. **Barista:** \\"Good morning! What can I get for you today?\\" Now, it's your turn to respond. Remember, it's okay to keep it simple since you're practicing at an A1 level."},{"instruction":"yes recently i fall in love to brew coffee","output":"Great! Let's break down your sentence, \\"*Yes, recently I fell in love with brewing coffee.*\\" First off, it's fantastic that you're trying to express a complex idea. Here are some points to help refine your sentence: 1. **Correction and Explanation**: - Your original sentence: \\"Yes recently I fall in love to brew coffee.\\" - A corrected version: \\"Yes, recently I fell in love with brewing coffee.\\" 2. **Details**: - **Yes,** - It‚Äôs good to start with \\"Yes\\" in response to the barista. It acknowledges the question. - **recently** - You correctly used \\"recently\\" to indicate that this interest in coffee is new. - **I fell in love** - You used \\"fall in love\\" to express developing a passion for something, but the tense needs to be past for this context, so \\"fell\\" is the correct choice. - **with brewing coffee** - The phrase \\"to brew coffee\\" should be \\"with brewing coffee\\" to correctly express your new-found interest. \\"With\\" is used before gerunds (verbs acting as nouns, here it's \\"brewing\\") when talking about interests or passions. 3. **Grammar Points**: - **Past Tense**: Since you're talking about something that started in the past and continues to the present, \\"fell\\" is the correct past tense form of \\"fall\\". - **Prepositions and Verbs**: The verb \\"fall in love\\" pairs with the preposition \\"with,\\" especially when followed by a gerund like \\"brewing\\". - **Commas in sentences**: After \\"Yes,\\" it's common to use a comma, especially when followed by another clause or phrase. To continue our role-play: **You**: \\"Yes, recently I fell in love with brewing coffee. Could I have a medium-sized coffee and a piece of cake, please?\\" This makes your interest clear and smoothly transitions into your order. Now, how about you try to respond to the barista asking which type of cake you'd like? Remember to keep it simple and use what you've learned so far!"},{"instruction":"tell me about the genetic predisposition of smbd who very easily rips parts of his muscles during training but has no pain afterwards, just visible small dents","output":"Experiencing muscle tears with little to no pain during physical activity might suggest an atypical response to muscle injury or an unusual pain threshold, possibly due to genetic factors or underlying conditions. While a definitive diagnosis can only be made through clinical evaluation, several possibilities could explain such occurrences, including but not limited to: 1. **Connective Tissue Disorders**: Certain genetic disorders like Ehlers-Danlos syndrome (EDS) or Marfan syndrome affect the body's connective tissues, which can make them more elastic or fragile than normal. This might lead to easier tearing of the muscle fibers or their attachments without necessarily causing typical pain responses due to the altered structure of connective tissues. People with these conditions often have an unusual range of motion and might not experience pain in the same way as others do. 2. **Muscular Dystrophies**: Some forms of muscular dystrophy, which are inherited conditions that cause progressive muscle weakness and loss of muscle mass, could potentially lead to increased susceptibility to muscle damage. However, these conditions typically also involve noticeable muscle weakness and other symptoms that would likely be detected early in life. 3. **Pain Insensitivity Disorders**: Rare genetic conditions that affect the nervous system can lead to congenital insensitivity to pain, meaning individuals might not feel pain in the way most people do. If muscle damage occurs, they may not experience it as pain or might have a significantly delayed or diminished pain response. 4. **Atypical Healing Responses**: There could also be genetic variations that affect the inflammatory response to injury, leading to either reduced pain sensation or altered healing processes that make the presence of injury less noticeable. It's important to understand that visible changes in the muscle, such as dents or deformities following physical activity, are not typical and warrant medical attention to rule out serious conditions. Genetic predispositions to such phenomena would likely be part of broader syndromes or conditions, as opposed to isolated genetic traits. If you or someone you know is experiencing these symptoms, it's crucial to consult with healthcare professionals who might recommend seeing a geneticist or a specialist in sports medicine, rheumatology, or neurology for comprehensive evaluation and genetic testing if appropriate. Identifying the underlying cause is important for managing health, preventing further injury, and tailoring a safe exercise regimen."},{"instruction":"In currently existing DC universe...what cities that seem to combine Gotham with Metropolis?","output":"In the DC Universe, Gotham City and Metropolis are two of the most iconic cities, each with its own distinct characteristics and vibes. Gotham City, home to Batman, is often depicted as a darker, grittier urban environment plagued by crime and corruption. It resembles cities like New York City in its worst eras or a perpetually dark, Gothic version of Chicago. On the other hand, Metropolis, home to Superman, is depicted as a bright, shining city of tomorrow, symbolizing hope, advancement, and optimism, and similarly draws inspiration from cities like New York City, with elements of Chicago and Toronto at times. While no city in the DC Universe is explicitly designed to be a combination of Gotham and Metropolis, several cities in comics share traits with both to various degrees, influenced by narrative needs and the creativity of the writers and artists. However, a city that \\"combines\\" both would inherently have characteristics of a large, technologically advanced city with a hopeful vibe, along with darker elements of crime and corruption. A few cities in the DC Universe have elements that could remind one of a mix between Gotham and Metropolis: 1. **Bl√ºdhaven** - Often depicted as a city even more corrupt than Gotham, it has served as the base for Dick Grayson (Nightwing) after he moved on from being Batman's sidekick. While traditionally not showing as many positive elements as Metropolis, Bl√ºdhaven exemplifies the urban decay and crime themes of Gotham, but its efforts towards rejuvenation and the presence of heroes like Nightwing lend it a touch of optimism. 2. **Star City** - The home of Green Arrow (Oliver Queen), combines elements of forested areas with an urban environment. It has its share of dark, crime-ridden areas similar to Gotham but also is a place of considerable technological advancements and has a certain vibrancy that can be reminiscent of Metropolis. 3. **Central City** - Known as the base for The Flash (Barry Allen), is another example. It's depicted as a city with a positive outlook, advanced science facilities (echoing the technological optimism of Metropolis), and a generally upbeat vibe. However, it also faces threats from various villains and challenges, giving it a darker edge at times. None of these cities perfectly combine Gotham and Metropolis's characteristics as they lean more towards one or the other in various aspects. The concept of blending the two, however, would result in a fascinating setting, balancing the grit and crime of Gotham with the hope and advancement represented by Metropolis. Comics are constantly evolving, and writers enjoy playing with established norms, so a more blended approach could emerge in future storylines."},{"instruction":"Then make one up for me","output":"Certainly! Let‚Äôs craft a fictional city within the DC Universe that embodies the essence of both Gotham and Metropolis, creating a beautifully complex setting for stories. We‚Äôll call this city \\"Twilight City.\\" **Twilight City: A Canvas of Light and Shadows** **Geography:** Twilight City is strategically located between Gotham and Metropolis, bordering a vast ocean on one side and sprawling hills on the other. Its unique position makes it a crucial hub for commerce, innovation, and, unfortunately, crime. The city's architecture is a marvel, showcasing sleek, futuristic skyscrapers in its bustling downtown area, known as the Dawn District, which glows with the promise of tomorrow, reminiscent of Metropolis. In stark contrast, the outskirts and older districts, colloquially known as the Dusk Zones, harbor a labyrinth of narrow, shadowy streets and Gothic buildings, echoing the eerie charm of Gotham. **Economy and Society:** Twilight City thrives on a dynamic economy powered by cutting-edge technology firms, green energy startups, and a booming cultural scene, attracting optimists and dreamers from all corners. However, the city's rapid growth has also fostered deep economic disparities, leading to neglected neighborhoods where crime flourishes under the shadow of corrupt institutions‚Äîa playground for ambitious vigilantes and hardened criminals alike. **Heroes and Villains:** The city is protected by a guardian known as The Eclipse‚Äîa hero who embodies the duality of Twilight City. By day, The Eclipse is a brilliant innovator working to lift the city into a brighter future. By night, they don a different persona, becoming a vigilant defender fighting against the crime and corruption festering in the city‚Äôs underbelly. The city's complexity also gives rise to a pantheon of villains, ranging from high-tech thieves and mad scientists inspired by Metropolis's rogues, to more grounded, gritty criminals and crime bosses that would feel at home in Gotham. The ever-present conflict between light and darkness in Twilight City draws various heroes and anti-heroes, each with their agendas, further enriching the city‚Äôs lore. **Key Landmarks:** - The Horizon Tower: The city's tallest building, located in the Dawn District, symbolizes hope and progress. It houses the most advanced research facilities and offers stunning views of the entire city. - The Shadow Market: Hidden within the Dusk Zones, this black market deals in illicit technology and forbidden knowledge. It‚Äôs a place where the desperate and the daring converge. - The Twilight Bridge: An engineering masterpiece connecting the Dawn District with the Dusk Zones, symbolizing the city's constant struggle and balance between light and dark. **Narrative Themes:** Twilight City‚Äôs stories would weave through themes of duality and balance, exploring how light can emerge from darkness and how too much brightness can cast the deepest shadows. It's a place where every victory and every innovation carries weight, reflecting the city's larger battle with its own identity‚Äîa struggle between becoming a beacon of hope like Metropolis or succumbing to the darkness like Gotham. In Twilight City, every hero‚Äôs actions, every villain‚Äôs scheme, and every citizen's choice contribute to the ever-evolving mosaic of a city forever dancing on the edge between day and night."},{"instruction":"–ò—Å–ø—Ä–∞–≤—å –æ—à–∏–±–∫—É –≤ –∫–æ–¥–µ: for movement_type in df_stab_agg_by_movement_type['movement_type'].unique(): fig = go.Figure() fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=df_stab_7_days_agg_by_movement_type.loc[(df_stab_7_days_agg_by_movement_type['cum_sh'] < 500) & (df_stab_7_days_agg_by_movement_type['movement_type'] == movement_type), ['cum_sh']], y=df_stab_7_days_agg_by_movement_type['mean_speed_km_h'], mode='lines', name='–ë–æ–ª–µ–µ 7 –¥–Ω–µ–π –Ω–∞ —Å–µ—Ä–≤–∏—Å–µ', color='movement_type')) fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=df_stab_14_days_agg_by_movement_type.loc[(df_stab_14_days_agg_by_movement_type['cum_sh'] < 500) & (df_stab_14_days_agg_by_movement_type['movement_type'] == movement_type), ['cum_sh']], y=df_stab_14_days_agg_by_movement_type['mean_speed_km_h'], mode='lines', name='–ë–æ–ª–µ–µ 14 –¥–Ω–µ–π –Ω–∞ —Å–µ—Ä–≤–∏—Å–µ', color='movement_t